'''Kamo Shrine''' (??????) is a {{jalink|shrine|Q845945}} in {{jalink|Kita-ku (Saitama)|Q542542|Kita Ward}}, {{jalink|Saitama|Q134635}}, {{jalink|Saitama Prefecture|Q128186}}.

=== History ===
Its founding date is unknown. However, it is said to be the origin of the "miya" in the local place name {{jalink|Miyahara-ch? (Saitama)|Q11453414|Miyahara-ch?}}<ref>For details, see {{jalink|Miyahara Village (Saitama Prefecture)|Q11453404|Miyahara Village}} and {{jalink|Miyahara-ch? (Saitama)|Q11453414|Miyahara-ch?}}.</ref>, and to have been founded by inviting a divided spirit from {{jalink|Kamo Wake-ikazuchi Shrine|Q700448}} of {{jalink|Yamashiro Province|Q749276}} Ichinomiya. {{jalink|Kissh?in (Kita-ku, Saitama)|Q124483193|Kissh?in}} in the same ward served as its {{jalink|bett?ji|Q11396755}}<ref name="??">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Office Shrine Survey Group (ed.), ''Shrines of Saitama: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama'', Saitama Prefecture Shrine Office, 1998, pp. 224-225</ref>.

In {{jalink|1873|Q7757}} (Meiji 6), it was ranked as a village shrine under the {{jalink|Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534}}, and during shrine mergers in the late Meiji period, surrounding shrines were merged into it. In {{jalink|1919|Q2157}} (Taish? 8), the worship hall burned down<ref name="??"></ref>.

=== Access ===
* 8 minutes on foot from {{jalink|Miyahara Station|Q845070}}.

