'''Kamo Shrine''' (??????) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} in {{ill|lt=Kita-ku (Saitama)|Q542542|WD=Q542542|lt=Kita Ward}}, {{ill|lt=Saitama|Q134635|WD=Q134635}}, {{ill|lt=Saitama Prefecture|Q128186|WD=Q128186}}.

=== History ===
Its founding date is unknown. However, it is said to be the origin of the "miya" in the local place name {{ill|lt=Miyahara-ch? (Saitama)|Q11453414|WD=Q11453414|lt=Miyahara-ch?}}<ref>For details, see {{ill|lt=Miyahara Village (Saitama Prefecture)|Q11453404|WD=Q11453404|lt=Miyahara Village}} and {{ill|lt=Miyahara-ch? (Saitama)|Q11453414|WD=Q11453414|lt=Miyahara-ch?}}.</ref>, and to have been founded by inviting a divided spirit from {{ill|lt=Kamo Wake-ikazuchi Shrine|Q700448|WD=Q700448}} of {{ill|lt=Yamashiro Province|Q749276|WD=Q749276}} Ichinomiya. {{ill|lt=Kissh?in (Kita-ku, Saitama)|Q124483193|WD=Q124483193|lt=Kissh?in}} in the same ward served as its {{ill|lt=bett?ji|Q11396755|WD=Q11396755}}<ref name="??">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Office Shrine Survey Group (ed.), ''Shrines of Saitama: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama'', Saitama Prefecture Shrine Office, 1998, pp. 224-225</ref>.

In {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757}} (Meiji 6), it was ranked as a village shrine under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534}}, and during shrine mergers in the late Meiji period, surrounding shrines were merged into it. In {{ill|lt=1919|Q2157|WD=Q2157}} (Taish? 8), the worship hall burned down<ref name="??"></ref>.

=== Access ===
* 8 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Miyahara Station|Q845070|WD=Q845070}}.

